        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>GBP optimization</strong> is the practice of fully configuring, maintaining, and actively managing a Google Business Profile so it ranks as high as possible in the Local Pack, Google Maps, and local search results. It covers profile completeness, category selection, reviews, photos, posts, and NAP consistency. Complete profiles are <strong>2.7x more likely to be considered reputable</strong> and rank materially higher than half-configured ones.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking weight</div>
            <div class="tms-value"><span class="http-code-chip ok">~36% of Local Pack</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO · GBP</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Time to first impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">4-8 weeks</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">For any business with a physical location or a defined service area, GBP is the highest-leverage marketing asset you own. Optimize it well and it delivers Local Pack impressions, calls, and directions requests month after month at zero media spend.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is GBP optimization?</h2>
        <p>GBP optimization is the discipline of turning a Google Business Profile from a stub — name, address, phone — into a fully populated, actively maintained storefront that Google trusts enough to rank in the Local Pack. It combines one-time setup work (categories, description, attributes) with ongoing operations (posts, reviews, photos, Q&amp;A).</p>
        <p>The category itself covers six overlapping optimization tracks:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Profile completeness</strong> — every field filled with accurate, keyword-informed data</li>
          <li><strong>Category selection</strong> — primary category plus 2-5 secondary categories</li>
          <li><strong>Review generation and response</strong> — quantity, freshness, and reply cadence</li>
          <li><strong>Content posting</strong> — weekly updates, offers, events</li>
          <li><strong>Visual assets</strong> — logo, cover, interior, exterior, team, product photos</li>
          <li><strong>NAP consistency</strong> — name, address, phone matched across citations</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why Google weights GBP so heavily</div>
          <p>Google's Local Pack surfaces first-party business data at the top of the results page. A well-optimized profile signals that the business is real, active, and worth showing to searchers — which is why Whitespark's annual factor survey attributes roughly <strong>36% of Local Pack ranking weight to GBP signals</strong>, more than any other single input.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why GBP optimization matters</h2>
        <p>For any business chasing local demand, GBP is the highest-leverage marketing asset available. Five reasons every local operator obsesses over it:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Local Pack visibility.</strong> GBP signals account for roughly 36% of Local Pack ranking factors. No other lever moves local rankings faster.</li>
          <li><strong>First impression control.</strong> For most local searches, the listing — not the website — is the first thing a prospect sees. Photos, reviews, and hours are the trust signals that convert.</li>
          <li><strong>Reviews live on the profile.</strong> 87% of consumers read online reviews for local businesses before deciding. Google Reviews on GBP influence both rankings and purchase intent.</li>
          <li><strong>Free marketing real estate.</strong> Posts, offers, Q&amp;A, and product listings appear on the SERP without paid placement.</li>
          <li><strong>Freshness signals.</strong> Weekly activity — posts, photos, review replies — signals to Google that the business is operating, which correlates with higher rankings.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How GBP optimization works</h2>
        <p>Optimization follows a four-track playbook that combines one-time setup with ongoing maintenance.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The four tracks of GBP optimization</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">1.</span> Complete every field <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">baseline signal</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">2.</span> Pick primary + 2-5 secondary categories <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">relevance signal</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">3.</span> Manage reviews (request + reply under 48h) <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">prominence signal</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">4.</span> Post weekly + refresh photos monthly <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">freshness signal</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Track 1 — Complete every field</h3>
        <p>Business name, categories, address, phone, website, hours, description, services, attributes, opening date, and holiday hours. A field left blank is a signal to Google that the profile is not fully claimed.</p>

        <h3>Track 2 — Choose the right categories</h3>
        <p>Primary category has the single biggest impact on which searches the listing appears for. Prefer specificity — "Emergency Plumber" over "Plumber", "Vegan Restaurant" over "Restaurant" — and add 2-5 secondary categories to expand coverage without diluting relevance.</p>

        <h3>Track 3 — Manage reviews actively</h3>
        <p>Set up a review request cadence for customers post-purchase. Respond to every review within 24-48 hours. Reply cadence and quality are both signals Google's Local Pack algorithm can measure.</p>

        <h3>Track 4 — Post and refresh regularly</h3>
        <p>Publish a GBP post at least weekly — 2-3 per week if you can — since posts expire after 7 days. Add photos monthly. Rotate services and offers.</p>

