        <p>Automated GBP posting through theStacc's Local SEO module so the profile stayed active without manual work every week. Combined with a review reply cadence, the profile held Local Pack top 3 across seasonal demand swings.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">GBP optimization vs local SEO — where the line sits</h2>
        <p>GBP optimization is one component of a broader local SEO practice. Local SEO also includes on-page work (location pages, schema), off-page work (citations, local backlinks), and reputation work outside Google.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>GBP optimization covers</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Everything inside the Google Business Profile dashboard</li>
              <li>Reviews on the Google profile</li>
              <li>Photos, posts, products, services on the profile</li>
              <li>Q&amp;A visible on the listing</li>
              <li>Google Maps ranking specifically</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Broader local SEO also includes</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Location and city pages on the website</li>
              <li>LocalBusiness schema markup</li>
              <li>Citation building on Yelp, BBB, Apple Business Connect</li>
              <li>Local backlinks and PR</li>
              <li>Reviews on non-Google platforms</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for GBP optimization in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Audit the profile quarterly.</strong> Google adds new fields and features constantly. A profile complete in January often has three empty fields by April.</li>
          <li><strong>Post at least weekly, ideally 2-3 times.</strong> Posts expire after 7 days. A profile with no posts in the last week looks inactive.</li>
          <li><strong>Reply to every review within 48 hours.</strong> Includes negatives. Reply quality is a trust signal for both Google and prospects reading the listing.</li>
          <li><strong>Aim for 25+ photos minimum, refresh monthly.</strong> Use every category — logo, cover, interior, exterior, team, product. Businesses with 100+ photos see 520% more calls.</li>
          <li><strong>Automate the repeatable work.</strong> Weekly posts, photo refreshes, review-request emails — all can be automated so consistency does not depend on someone remembering.</li>
          <li><strong>Match NAP across every citation.</strong> Name, address, phone must be identical on Yelp, BBB, Apple Business Connect, industry directories.</li>
          <li><strong>Track rank in the map pack, not just organic.</strong> Local Pack rankings differ by search location. Use a geo-grid rank tracker to see where you actually appear.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — keyword-stuffing the business name</div>
          <p>Adding keywords to the business name field ("Bob's Plumbing - Emergency Plumber Denver") violates Google's guidelines and can trigger a suspension. Use the real legal business name only. Keywords belong in categories, services, and the description.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common GBP optimization mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Half-completed profile.</strong> Blank fields hurt the completeness signal. Fill everything, even the fields that feel optional.</li>
          <li><strong>Wrong primary category.</strong> "Restaurant" instead of "Italian Restaurant" hides you from the searches that convert.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring negative reviews.</strong> No response looks worse than a defensive one. Reply calmly and offer a resolution path.</li>
          <li><strong>Posting once, then stopping.</strong> The freshness signal decays fast. A single post from six months ago hurts more than not posting at all.</li>
          <li><strong>Uploading stock photos.</strong> Google's image quality signals prefer real business photos. Stock imagery can be flagged.</li>
          <li><strong>Duplicate listings.</strong> A second listing with the same NAP splits ranking signals. Merge or claim the duplicate.</li>
        </ul>

